Predicting Premier League Match Outcomes: A Machine Learning Tutorial

Introduction:

Accurate sports analytics represents a significant challenge in sports analytics with a multitude of factors needed to consider when determining the outcome. This project address this problem by determining which factors have the most signifcant contirbution in determining the end result for premier league matches and developing models based on these behaviors. With the English premier league being the most watched sports league in the world, a precise analysis is crucial for making informed decisions by clubs, analysts, and investors. Inaccurate modeling could result in poor team management, mis-investments, and signifcant financial losses.

The importance of this analysis extends beyond indvidual match days to long term strategy such as identifying if Expected Goals (xg) is a better predictor of future success than actual goals scored. Our investigation centers around answering these key questions: "Which historical statistics strongly correlate with scoring the most points?", "How effectively can machine learning models like Random Forest, Logistic Regression, and SVM predict match outcomes?", "How do we handle the statistical difficulty of predicting 'Draws'?". Through comprehensive analysis of the Premier League match data, we hope to develop a robust predictive model while providing insights into the predictive analysis.

2. Data Curation: Data Cleaning & Optimization

Link to dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mhmdkardosha/premier-league-matches/data

NOTE: For a key of all the soccer statistic abbreviations used here, visit the link above. We have not pasted it here for the sake of readability, as it is quite long.

Real world sports data is often messy with a lot of noise making it rarely ready for immediate analysis especially if we want to use this data for a model.In the section below after loading matches.csv we then reduce noise, do some temporal formatting, and categroical optimization.

  • Noise Reduction consists of dropping columns like comp, notes, and match report, which provide context for human readers but no vlaue for models.
  • Temporal Formatting consists of converting the date column into the Python datetime format for chronological ordering.
  • Categorical Optimization consists of converting object coumns like venue and opponent into categorical data to optimize memory usage and processing speed.

Another crucial step we need to handle is the season alignment. In the Premier league a season often times spans across 2 years. To fix this the correction logic we implement is by classifying anything played from August till the end of the year is grouped into the following years' season. This would make it so that anything played from August-December 2023 is part of the 2024 season, while anything played from January-July 2023 is still part of the current 2023 season. This ensures all matches belong to their proper season and the rolling averages we calculate are accurate.

3. Feature Engineering:

To predict the outcome of a match we cannot use statistics from the match itself or any future predictors. Hence we rely on past performance. Since the direct past performance wouldn't be a good indicator for what transpires in the coming match we create "Rolling Averages" for key metrics like Goals for(gf), Expected Gaols(xg), etc. By averaging these stats across the past 5 games we create a good metric for the teams current form and how they will most likley perform in their coming match. We then drop any original match specific columns to prevent data leakage.

#Converting to proper python date and times formats
df["hour"] = df["time"].str.replace(":.+", "", regex=True).astype("int")
df["day_code"] = df["date"].dt.dayofweek

#Removing columns that are missing data, there are very few so we can simply remove them
df.dropna(inplace=True)

#Checking data for duplicates
print("number of duplicates", df.duplicated().sum())

df.dropna(inplace=True)
df.formation.value_counts()

#Changing formation into a more readable format
df.formation = df.formation.str.replace("", "")

df.formation.value_counts()

#We need to fix some errors with season labeling, as explained above
print("seasons before", df["season"].unique())

#Sorting data by date and team to make sure the next steps work
df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["date"])
df = df.sort_values(["team", "date"]).reset_index(drop=True)

# Extract year and month
year = df["date"].dt.year
month = df["date"].dt.month

# Compute correct season: AugDec belong to next year, JanJul to current year
df["season"] = np.where(month >= 8, year + 1, year).astype(int)

#seasons are now correctly defined
print("seasons after",df["season"].unique())

# Ensure correct ordering
df = df.sort_values(["team", "season", "date"]).reset_index(drop=True)

df["goal_diff"] = df["gf"] - df["ga"] #making a goal differential column
df["points"] = df["result"].map({"W": 3, "D": 1, "L": 0}) #This is a useful mapping for record

# Stats we want rolling averages for
rolling_stats = ["gf", "ga", "xg", "xga", "sh", "sot", "poss", "goal_diff", "points"]

# Rolling window size: 5 games
window = 5

print("Rows before:", len(df)) #Printing out rows before we do data revision, so that we know exactly how much we are deleting

#This loop computes the rolling averages for the previous [window] games, we are using window=5.
for col in rolling_stats: #for each stat in the rolling_stats array
  df[f"{col}_roll{window}"] = (
      df.groupby(["team", "season"], observed=False)[col] #compute these by team
      .shift(1) # only can use past matches
      .rolling(window) # how many previous games we are averaging over, 5 in this case
      .mean() #average
      .reset_index(level=0, drop=True) #Maintaining indicies
  )

explore_df = df.copy(deep=True) #saving for exploratory data analysis later

df = df.dropna() #drop those first 5 games, since their rolling stats are NaN (can't compute the average of the last 5 games for the 3rd game of the season)

#we should have dropped 5 per team, 20 teams, 5 seasons: 5x20x5=500, so we can see we dropped precisely the corect number of games; we did everything right
print("Rows after dropping early-season rows:", len(df))

3. Target Creation and Exploratory Data Analysis

Before building our model we need to start by deifning our target and understanding the properites of our data.

Defining our Target: Our goal is to predict the match outcome: Win, Draw, or Loss. We do this by converting our points column (3,1,0) into these categorical values to serve as target variables for our classifier with Win,Draw,Loss representing those numbers respectively.

Analyzing Class Balance: In football the frequency of a "Draw" is signifcantly lower than a "Win" or "Loss" occuring. This class imbalance is crucial as standard machine learning models struggle with minority classes like this and this often results in inaccuracies as they would prefer to predict a majority to maximize overall accuracies.

Validating Features: We also want to see that our rolling average features actually contain predictive signals so we create boxplots to compare the distribution of Rolling Expected Goals for each outcome and expect to see teams with higher median in the box plot have more Wins.

Exploratory Data Analysis

We will now perform some statistical tests to better understand how some of the variables in our dataset correlate with one another. We will investigate:

  1. Do teams win significantly more often at home vs away?
  • We will use a two sample z-test with win percentage to determine this
  1. Which performance features (shots, possession, fouls, etc.) correlate the most with home wins?
  • We will use Linear Regression and a likihood ratio test to determine this
  1. Does goal differential strongly predict total points or final league position?
  • We will use a Pearson Correkaton test between Goal Differential (GD) and points + league position

Question: Do teams win significantly more often when playing at home compared to away?

Method: Two sample z-test with win percantage at home versus away.

Hypothesis:

Hypothesis: H0: The proportion of home wins equals the proportion of away wins. H1: The proportion of home wins is greater than the proportion of away wins.

Testing type: Two-Sample Z-test See cells below for data visualization and test statistic computation, computed z-value = 6.61458, computed p-value of 0.00000.

Conclusion Found:

We reject H0; home teams win significantly more often (p = 0.00000 < 0.05). Thus, home field advantage significantly increases winning percentage.

#1: Do teams win more at home?
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

counts = explore_df.groupby(['venue', 'result']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)

rates = counts.div(counts.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100

home_wins = len(explore_df[(explore_df['venue'] == 'Home') & (explore_df['result'] == 'W')])
away_wins = len(explore_df[(explore_df['venue'] == 'Away') & (explore_df['result'] == 'W')])

home_games = len(explore_df[explore_df['venue'] == 'Home'])
away_games = len(explore_df[explore_df['venue'] == 'Away'])

hwhg = home_wins/home_games
awag = away_wins/away_games

print(f"Home wins: {home_wins}/{home_games} = {hwhg:.5f}")
print(f"Away wins: {away_wins}/{away_games} = {awag:.5f}")

#running two sample t-test
z_stat, p_val = proportions_ztest([home_wins, away_wins], [home_games, away_games], alternative='larger')

print(f"Z-statistic: {z_stat:.5f}")
print(f"P-value: {p_val:.5f}")

#2: Which performance features correlate most with home wins?
import statsmodels.api as sm
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf
from scipy.stats import chi2

# 1. Keep only home games
home_df = explore_df[explore_df['venue'] == 'Home'].copy()

mapping = {'L': 1, 'D': 0, 'W': 2}
home_df['result_code'] = home_df['result'].map(mapping)
# Define the model formula  include all features
features = "poss + xg + xga + ga + sot + sh + fk + pk + dist"
formula = f"result ~ {features}"

X = home_df[[ 'poss','xg', 'xga', 'ga', 'sot', 'sh', 'fk', 'pk', 'dist']]

# 4. Add intercept term
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# 5. Fit multinomial logistic regression
model = sm.MNLogit(home_df['result_code'], X)
result = model.fit(method='newton', maxiter=200, disp=False)
print(result.model.endog_names)
print(result.model._ynames_map)
print(result.summary())

# Fit null model (intercept only)
X_null = sm.add_constant(pd.DataFrame({'const': 1}, index=home_df.index))
null_model = sm.MNLogit(home_df['result_code'], X_null)
null_result = null_model.fit(method='newton', disp=False)

# Likelihood ratio test
LR_stat = 2 * (result.llf - null_result.llf)
df_diff = result.df_model - null_result.df_model
p_value = chi2.sf(LR_stat, df_diff)

print(f"\nLikelihood Ratio Test:")
print(f"LR stat = {LR_stat:.3f}, df = {df_diff}, p = {p_value:.4g}")

#Lets plot the results!
# Drop the intercept if you want to focus on features
coef_df = result.params.drop(columns='const', errors='ignore')

# Transpose so features are rows
coef_plot = coef_df.T

# Plot grouped bars
order = coef_plot.abs().max(axis=1).sort_values(ascending=False).index
coef_plot.loc[order].plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10,6))
plt.axhline(0, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)
plt.title('Feature Coefficients by Outcome (vs Loss)')
plt.ylabel('Log-Odds Coefficient')
plt.xlabel('Feature (0=draw vs loss, 1=win vs loss)')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.legend(title='Outcome vs Loss')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Question:

Does the goal differential feature strongly predict total points or final league position?

Method:

Pearson Correlation test between GD and points + league position

Hypothesis:

H0: There is no correlation between GD and league position

H1: There is a significant correlation between GD and league position

Conclusion Found:

The Pearson correlation between goal differential and total points is .7755, indicating a very strong positive linear relationship. Teams with higher goal differentials earn more points.

The correlation between differential and final league position is -.8424, meaning that higher goal differntials correspond to better league standings.

With that, we are able to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that goal differential is a strong predictor of both total points and final league rank.

#3: Does goal differential strongly predict total points or final league position?
season_stats = (
    explore_df.groupby(["season", "team"])
      .agg(
          goals_for=("gf", "sum"),
          goals_against=("ga", "sum"),
          wins=("result", lambda x: (x == "W").sum()),
          draws=("result", lambda x: (x == "D").sum()),
          losses=("result", lambda x: (x == "L").sum())
      )
      .reset_index()
)

# Compute derived features
season_stats["GD"] = season_stats["goals_for"] - season_stats["goals_against"]
season_stats["Points"] = 3 * season_stats["wins"] + season_stats["draws"]

# Rank teams by points for each season (lower rank = better)
season_stats["Position"] = season_stats.groupby("season")["Points"].rank(ascending=False, method="first")

from scipy.stats import pearsonr

# Drop rows with NaN values in GD, Points, or Position
season_stats_cleaned = season_stats.dropna(subset=["GD", "Points", "Position"])

# Calculate Pearson correlation between GD and Points
correlation_gd_points, p_value_gd_points = pearsonr(season_stats_cleaned["GD"], season_stats_cleaned["Points"])

# Calculate Pearson correlation between GD and Position
correlation_gd_position, p_value_gd_position = pearsonr(season_stats_cleaned["GD"], season_stats_cleaned["Position"])

print(f"Pearson correlation between Goal Differential and Season Points: {correlation_gd_points:.4f} (p-value: {p_value_gd_points:.4f})")
print(f"Pearson correlation between Goal Differential and Season Position: {correlation_gd_position:.4f} (p-value: {p_value_gd_position:.4f})")

4. Data Splitting & Processing

In sports analytics random splitting is inappropriate as it can cause random data leakages that we won't know how to account for. In our case we want to implement a temporal split as we do not want to use future matches to predict past ones.

With a temporal split we segrgeate the data based on the seasons with all the seasons prior to 2024 used for model training and the 2024 season remains used for model testing. This ensures that our evaluation metric best reflect the model's ability to predict future games.

In[]:
train_df = df[df["season"] < 2024]
test_df = df[df["season"] == 2024]

print(f"Shape of training data: {train_df.shape}")
print(f"Shape of testing data: {test_df.shape}")

Shape of training data: (3626, 26)
Shape of testing data: (660, 26)

The split results in 3,626 samples for training and 660 for testing. This provides a robust historical baseline for the model while reserving a full season's worth of games for evaluation, which is sufficient to smooth out variance from individual match upsets.

5. Primary Analysis: Building Prediction Pipelines and Evaluations

RANDOM FOREST PIPELINE

We make use of Scikit-Learn's Pipeline class to guarantee an efficient and repeatable approach. The machine learning model and our previously specified preprocessing are combined into one object by this wrapper. This simplifies the code for next predictions and stops "data leakage," which occurs when knowledge from the test set unintentionally seeps into the training process.

For this challenge, we have used the Random Forest Classifier. During training, Random Forests are ensemble learning techniques that build a large number of decision trees. Because they are resistant to overfitting and can manage the non-linear relationships frequently found in match statistics, they are especially well-suited for sports prediction.

In[]:
X_train = train_df[numerical_features + categorical_features]
y_train = train_df["target"]

TRAIN LOG REG

Despite feature engineering, our Random Forest model continued to ignore the "Draw" class. The model optimizes for overall accuracy by merely predicting the majority classes ,Win/Loss, which is a common problem when one class is much smaller than the others.

We use a Logistic Regression model to combat this. In contrast to the Random Forest that was previously employed, we will specifically set class_weight='balanced'. This input tells the model to modify the loss function so that errors on the minority class ,Draws, are penalized more severely than errors on the majority classes. This should ideally compel the model to "pay attention" to games that are tied.

In[]:

Logistic Regression Coefficient Visualization

Logistic regression is much easier to understand than the hidden functonality of complex models. For each feature, the model learns a particular coefficient, or weight. Positive Coefficients: Raise the positive class's log-odds (for example, a higher xg increases the likelihood of a "Win"). Negative Coefficients: Reduce the log-odds (for example, a higher xga reduces the likelihood of a "Win"). The top coefficients influencing the model's decision-making are shown in the plot below. This enables us to determine precisely which statistics the model is "betting on."

Train SVM Model

We use a Support Vector Machine (SVM) as a last experiment. In high-dimensional space, SVMs are effective at locating intricate decision boundaries.

Important Preprocessing Step: SVMs are distance-based algorithms, in contrast to Random Forests. To determine the ideal "hyperplane" that divides classes, they compute the mathematical distance between data points. The feature with the greater range will control the distance calculation if our features have radically different scales (for example, points_roll5 ranges from 0-15 while xg is 0-3).

We need to update our ColumnTransformer to incorporate a StandardScaler for the numerical features in order to avoid this. This sets the mean and standard deviation of all numerical inputs to 0 and 1, respectively.

Visualizing SVM Feature Importance (Permutation Method)

Our SVM has no linear coefficients to plot because it employs a non-linear RBF kernel, in contrast to Logistic Regression. It is impossible to directly visualize the model because it exists in a high-dimensional space.

We use Permutation Importance to determine which features influence the SVM's choices. Using this method, one feature column in the test set is shuffled at random, and the accuracy of the model is then measured. Large Drop: The prediction relied heavily on this feature. Zero/Small Drop: This feature was hardly utilized by the model.

Interpretation of Permutation Importance

The "Drop" Metric: The percentage of accuracy lost when a feature is corrupted is shown on the X-axis. For instance, if xg_roll5 is 0.05, then eliminating that data results in a 5% decrease in accuracy. Comparing This Model with Others: Are these characteristics the same as those found in the Random Forest? The SVM's performance was significantly different if it relies on entirely different features.

Negative Values Bars may appear somewhat negative. This simply indicates that the noisy feature was probably irrelevant or confusing to the SVM because shuffling it actually improved the model by chance.

preprocessor_svm = svm_pipeline.named_steps['preprocessor']

# This satisfies the "array-like" requirement of permutation_importance

Calculate Rolling Season Record

Objective:

We want to calculate a new feature rolling_season_record for each team within each season. This feature will represent the team's record up to the current game, calculated as (previous_wins + 0.5 * previous_draws) / total_previous_games_played. This will require cumulative sums of wins, draws, and games played, shifted by one to avoid data leakage.

In[]:
df["wins"] = (df["target"] == "Win").astype(int)
df["draws"] = (df["target"] == "Draw").astype(int)
df["total_games_played"] = 1

print(df[["target", "wins", "draws", "total_games_played"]].head())

  target  wins  draws  total_games_played
5    Win     1      0                   1
6   Draw     0      1                   1
7    Win     1      0                   1
8   Loss     0      0                   1
9   Draw     0      1                   1

Now that the 'wins', 'draws', and 'total_games_played' columns are created, we will group the DataFrame by 'team' and 'season', calculate the cumulative sum of these columns, and then shift them by one to get the 'previous' values. This is crucial for avoiding data leakage and correctly computing the rolling record.

In[]:
grouped = df.groupby(['team', 'season'], observed=False)

df["previous_wins"] = grouped["wins"].cumsum().shift(1)
df["previous_draws"] = grouped["draws"].cumsum().shift(1)
df["total_previous_games_played"] = grouped["total_games_played"].cumsum().shift(1)

# Fill NaN values (which occur for the first game of each season for each team) with 0
df["previous_wins"] = df["previous_wins"].fillna(0)
df["previous_draws"] = df["previous_draws"].fillna(0)
df["total_previous_games_played"] = df["total_previous_games_played"].fillna(0)

# Calculate rolling_season_record, handling division by zero for initial games
df["rolling_season_record"] = np.where(
    df["total_previous_games_played"] > 0,
    (df["previous_wins"] + 0.5 * df["previous_draws"]) / df["total_previous_games_played"],
    0  # Assign 0 for the first game of the season or if no previous games
)

# Display the new feature and its components
print(df[["team", "season", "date", "target", "wins", "draws", "total_games_played",
          "previous_wins", "previous_draws", "total_previous_games_played",
          "rolling_season_record"]].head(10))

Redefine Preprocessor (Imputer & Scaler)

Redefine the ColumnTransformer to include SimpleImputer(strategy='mean') for numerical features, followed by a StandardScaler. This will handle any NaN values from new features and ensure proper scaling for all numerical features. Afterwards we redefine the ColumnTransformer named preprocessor to include OneHotEncoder for categorical features and a Pipeline of SimpleImputer and StandardScaler for numerical features

In[]:
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer

print("SimpleImputer imported successfully.")

SimpleImputer imported successfully.
In[]:
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'), categorical_features),
        ('num', Pipeline(steps=[('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')),
                               ('scaler', StandardScaler())]), numerical_features)
    ])

  • SVM: Recall = 0.34, F1-score = 0.33
  • Logistic Regression: Recall = 0.20, F1-score = 0.23
  • Random Forest: Recall = 0.04, F1-score = 0.08

Compared to the previous iteration (before rolling_season_record), the SVM model's recall for 'Draw' slightly improved from 0.33 to 0.34, and its F1-score remained stable at 0.32/0.33. This indicates a minor positive impact or at least stability for SVM in handling draws with the new feature. Random Forest and Logistic Regression saw slight decreases or remained stagnant in their 'Draw' metrics with this new feature.

Key Strengths and Weaknesses:

  • Random Forest:

    • Strengths: Achieved the highest overall accuracy (0.60) and maintained strong performance for 'Win' and 'Loss' predictions (high recall and F1-score). It generally handles non-linear relationships well.
    • Weaknesses: Continues to exhibit extremely poor performance in predicting 'Draw' outcomes, with very low recall and F1-score. The rolling_season_record feature did not help significantly in this regard.

  • Logistic Regression:

    • Strengths: With class_weight='balanced', it provided a better balance in 'Draw' prediction compared to Random Forest (higher recall and F1-score for 'Draw'), though performance slightly dipped with the new feature. Its overall accuracy is decent (0.58).
    • Weaknesses: Slightly lower overall accuracy than Random Forest. The F1-score for 'Draw' predictions decreased from 0.29 to 0.23 with the new feature, indicating it didn't benefit from rolling_season_record for this class.

  • SVM:

    • Strengths: Achieved the best performance in predicting 'Draw' outcomes (highest recall and F1-score for 'Draw') among the three models, showing a slight improvement in recall with the new feature. The StandardScaler and class_weight='balanced' were crucial for this.
    • Weaknesses: Tied for the lowest overall accuracy (0.58) among the three models. Performance for 'Win' and 'Loss' is generally lower than Random Forest. SVMs can also be computationally expensive for large datasets.

Conclusion: While the rolling_season_record feature and updated preprocessing did not dramatically alter the overall landscape, the SVM model continues to be the most effective in identifying 'Draw' outcomes, demonstrating the best balance between precision and recall for this challenging class. Random Forest maintains the highest overall accuracy but struggles severely with 'Draws'. Logistic Regression shows moderate performance across the board but did not significantly benefit from the new feature for 'Draw' predictions.

Final Conclusion

Effectiveness of Models, and Feature Impact

While the model had difficulty with draws, it was still able to accurately identify a majority of the win and loss classifiers noted by the deep blue color on each of the confusion charts. Overall the most useful features where expected goals, which means that games with large expected goals were likely to win, and games with large expected goals against generally lost. On the flip side, features such as the hour, season year, and day of the game, had little to no impact on the result of the game.

Draw handling

Ultimately despite the wide variety of models and features, the 'draw' classifier was the most difficult to predict. This likely due to the fact that draw has less samples compared the other classes and the draw class essentially is acting as the boundary between classifier of winning a losing, and will often be influenced by random chance beyond the specific feature. Its fully possible where most of the features are the same there's one small difference that leads to a draw when it good be in either teams favor. Overall the SVM was the most accurate in predicting draws which makes sense as SVMs tries to draw a borderline between classifiers using support vectors which often lie close to the borderline, these vectors likely closely match the features of the draw classifier.
